# .bridge-origin — identity of the upstream this Bridge's CORE was published from.
#
# Read by scripts/hooks/pre-push to decide whether a push target is the PUBLIC
# OSS upstream — the one place your USER data (identity/agent, work/, client
# content on a user/* branch) must never land.
#
# PER-REPO DIVERGENT, intentionally: the public open-bridge repo ships
# `is_public: true`; a PRIVATE downstream (your own clone re-homed to your own
# repo) sets `is_public: false` AND points `repo:` at that private origin's
# owner/name. Because the value differs per tier, /promote and /bridge-sync must
# NOT overwrite this file (same convention as the ecosystem self-entry and the
# .claude/commands tier slot).
#
# How the guard reads it (only when `repo:` matches the push TARGET — a stale
# marker from a previous origin never vouches for a re-homed remote):
#   is_public: true   → TARGET classified PUBLIC  → user/* / USER content BLOCKED
#   is_public: false  → TARGET classified PRIVATE → push ALLOWED (the deterministic,
#                       offline "this is my private origin, allow" signal)
# A target this file says nothing about (repo: mismatch) stays UNKNOWN, and the
# guard fails CLOSED for USER data — re-point `repo:` (or use
# bridge-config.yaml push_guard.private_remotes) after re-homing origin.
repo: bks-lab/open-bridge
is_public: true
